    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-08-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-08-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="1342"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1342">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.51/571a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">American Minister</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-08-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 17, 1913</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Send lists, approximately up to date, as follows:</p>
                <p>Nicaragua’s internal gold debt, with names of creditors, amounts, rates of
                    interest, and character of each debt.</p>
                <p>Debts to foreign correspondents or commission merchants, with the same data.</p>
                <p>Unpaid salaries to September 1, by departments or individuals.</p>
                <p>Amounts the Government has received monthly from customs, railway, liquor,
                    tobacco, and other revenues; cover the last three months in three separate
                    monthly lists.</p>
                <p>Expenditures or contracted obligations for the same three months as above.</p>
                <p>Send these lists by mail as soon as possible. Say to the President that they
                    should be as accurate as possible in order to assist the Department in its
                    sincere endeavor to aid in relieving Nicaragua financially.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
